+  lines.push(`- Pembrolizumab attenuation by autoimmune_disease was not supported (${round(interactions.pembrolizumab_autoimmune.beta)} months, p=${formatP(interactions.pembrolizumab_autoimmune.p)}).`);
+  lines.push(`- Regorafenib was adverse as a main effect (${round(global.treatment_regorafenib.beta)} months, p=${formatP(global.treatment_regorafenib.p)}), while the hypothesized worsening with higher ecog_ps was not significant (${round(interactions.regorafenib_ecog.beta)} months per ECOG point, p=${formatP(interactions.regorafenib_ecog.p)}).`);
+  lines.push(`- Autoimmune disease itself was not an independent adverse prognostic factor in the adjusted model (${round(global.autoimmune_disease.beta)} months, p=${formatP(global.autoimmune_disease.p)}).`);
+  lines.push("");
+  lines.push("Overall conclusion: the strongest patterns were clinically coherent treatment-biomarker relationships: pembrolizumab with MSI-high disease, encorafenib with BRAF V600E, trastuzumab/tucatinib with HER2 amplification, and reduced cetuximab benefit in RAS-mutant or right-sided disease. Baseline inflammatory, nutritional, and metastatic-burden variables also carried independent prognostic information for progression-free survival. Several safety/comorbidity interaction ideas were tested but not statistically supported in this cohort.");
